Positive End Expiratory Pressure (PEEP) can be both set and measured on the ventilator.
Measured PEEP can include distinct values such as total, extrinsic, and intrinsic PEEP.
When all these details are available, we recommend using the concept "Positive end expiratory pressure setting" for the value set on the ventilator, and "Intrinsic PEEP Respiratory system", "Extrinsic PEEP Respiratory system", or "Total PEEP Respiratory system" for the measured values.
Intrinsic and extrinsic PEEP values are typically obtained during an expiratory flow pause performed by the clinician. To differentiate PEEP values obtained with or without this maneuver, we suggest using "Total PEEP Respiratory system" for any measured PEEP, and specifying "Intrinsic PEEP Respiratory system" and "Extrinsic PEEP Respiratory system" only when a pause was performed to obtain them. Finally, if no detail is available about whether the PEEP is set or measured, the more generic concept "Positive end expiratory pressure" should be used.

Tidal volume can be both set and measured on the ventilator (with distinct inspiratory and expiratory values for the measured tidal volume).
When all this information is available, we recommend using the concept "Mandatory tidal volume" for the value set on the ventilator, and "Inspiratory tidal volume" or "Expiratory tidal volume" for the measured values.
If the measured tidal volume is documented but the source (inspiratory or expiratory) is not specified, we suggest using "Spontaneous tidal volume".
Finally, if no detail is available about whether the tidal volume is set or measured, the generic concept "Tidal volume" should be used.
